Chapter 23: Standard Components

The application MUST be built using reusable, composable React components. Never duplicate code for similar UI elements.

Core Component Library Requirements:

Cards: Customer Card, Machine Card, Operator Card, Statistics KPI Card, AI Insight Card, Assignment Card.

Panels: Customer Summary Panel, Machine Summary Panel, Glass Panel, Information Panel, AI Assistant Panel.

Lists/Tables: Table Toolbar, Pagination Component, Timeline.

Feedback: Status Badge, Notification Card, Loading Skeleton, Empty State, Error State, Toast.

Layout: Profile Header, Section Header, Breadcrumb, Page Header, Notification Drawer, Action Menu, Quick Action Widget, Chart Container, Recent Activity Widget.

Inputs: Search Bar, Filter Bar, Confirmation Dialog.

Chapter 24: Standard Table Behaviour

Every data table in the application must exhibit identical behavior and styling:

UI: Sticky table header, consistent spacing, row hover effect (bg-muted/50).

Interactions: Search input, sortable columns, pagination controls, filtering options.

Data Handling: Responsive horizontal scrolling (overflow-x-auto), loading skeleton while fetching, meaningful empty state if no records, error state if fetch fails.

Actions: Action menu (ellipses ... or dedicated buttons) per row, consistent status badges.

Rule: Large datasets must never load entirely at once. Pagination or infinite scroll is required.

Chapter 25: Standard Form Behaviour

Forms must be robust and user-friendly:

Required fields must be clearly indicated (e.g., with an asterisk *).

Save/Submit buttons MUST remain disabled until frontend validation passes.

Display inline validation error messages immediately below the respective input.

Buttons must show a loading state (spinner/text change) while the backend request is processing to prevent duplicate submissions.

Display a success or error toast upon completion.

Warn users (unsaved changes dialog) if they attempt to navigate away from a dirty form.

Use confirmation dialogs before major destructive or state-changing updates.

Chapter 26: Notification Behaviour

The notification system should feel real-time and engaging:

Unread indicator (red dot on the bell icon).

Real-time updates (Supabase Realtime subscriptions preferred).

Strictly role-specific (a user only sees notifications linked to their user_id).

Visual distinction between Read and Unread states.

"Mark All as Read" action.

Deep linking: Clicking a notification MUST navigate the user directly to the relevant entity (e.g., clicking a request notification goes to /admin/service-requests).

Group notifications by date (e.g., "Today", "Yesterday").

Show recent notifications first.

